Each transaction between two users is actually made between two e-mail addresses.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is electronically signed through a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the bitcoins changes consist of the public accounts book, which is disseminated throughout the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction in that book.
This goes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge to computers and the winner, a sort of temporary central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
This is a phase of file-cutting, i.e. transformation of a large file into a shorter and more unique numerical footprint.
Computers "take the new transaction" and add a number before "trace" the set.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular footprint (more zero at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the good one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the set chain of the other transactions; any change would change the footprint.
If, to commit a fraud, a user would want to pay twice with the same money very fast (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept as valid one of the two transactions; the other would be orphaned, since both have different footprints.
The computer that solves the challenge takes 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided into two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is, therefore, limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to 100 million, which leaves a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in each increase in the calculation power.
The life of the network already has its heights.
Websites that offer services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins have been stolen in storage.
"The fault used does not affect the same protocol," says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real currency payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
