A Constitution with Forceps in Egypt
It's a new double or nothing from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever in terms of the constitutional declaration, which provisionally gives it full powers, he decided to play the whole thing for the whole.
He caught everyone by surprise on Wednesday, when he announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of State had given the Assembly two more months to complete its work.
And for almost two years, Egypt has used a provisional text, several times changed, which weakens institutional stability and leads to judicial fraud.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the president perseveres in his "autocratic delusion" and continues "treasoning his word" and "strengthening the right".
On the part of its supporters, it is ensured that this is a step towards bringing an end to the institutional and political crisis and accelerating the transition process.
A referendum should be organized within the next 15 days.
A very short period of time that obliges the Brothers to give up their draft to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy while the controversy causes havoc throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote for him, as he said in an interview to the American weekly Time.
Considering that this appeal has been voted on very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "or vote on my text or keep the powers full", powers that are supposed to end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in that strange environment in which 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, Islamist in its great majority, voted the text yesterday.
Most liberals did not attend the call.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they felt they could not enforce their views.
The representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society did likewise.
In order to achieve the quorum needed, 11 persons, substitute members were added yesterday morning in a hurry.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brothers.
As was expected, the voting articles were unanimously.
The commentators are grateful, on the other hand, for the fact that one of the few discrepancies of the day has been expressed practically at the time of prayer, so that several members of the committee came to think that the clock of the Constituent was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on yesterday, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which is the subject of all the views, remains at last identical to the 1971 Constitution, which stipulated that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law".
Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental claim, hoped that "the principles" could be replaced by "the norms", which would have allowed a stricter application.
For Islamists, that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
The liberals are hypocritical and consider it to be nothing more than an advertising artimagin.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is made through other articles.
They refer, in particular, to article 220, which confers on Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular for anyone who must confirm their conformity with the laws of Sharia.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because "people called to pronounce themselves are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we glimpse the premises of a theocracy."
The fears of the Liberals are further increased by the fact that the next rector of that university would be quite less moderate than the current one.
"For now, there is no concrete religious implication.
With this Constitution we are within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked in that text are not ulemians but university students, some of them trained in the French system," explains Alexis Bluuet, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that there may be some ambiguity around article 220, for the terms used imitate religious vocabulary.
"We refer specifically to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question that might be raised in the future would be to what extent are the competent civil judges to decide above all this."
Beyond its religious character, the text voted yesterday has received many criticisms concerning the extended powers conferred on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brothers will claim that there are few compared to those during the previous regime.
Another conflicting point: the powers conferred on the army.
As the military wishes, the review of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Civil prosecutions in military courts will also not be prohibited, as requested by human rights associations.
These also showed their concerns regarding the text, which they consider to be libertizive.
The crime of blasphemy is maintained and, from now on, insults are prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially that of the press.
In addition, no article emphasizes the protection of women, stresses Heba Morayef, from Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive thing has been the prohibition of torture in accordance with article 36.
The word did not appear in the previous Constitution.
Although the Egyptian president was supposed to go out last night on television, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
The supporters of the Head of State manifested themselves on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists await the holy land, the world's obligation and a sea of salmon
The promised Earth combines the majesty of Bible truths with modern comfort and a pristine nature.
"AIF" identified the five most important reasons for visiting Israel.
Reverence in the Holy Land
It is worth visiting the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is believed that anyone who enters this "baptismal pillar" will receive divine grace.
And Galilee, the place of the miracles of Jesus: the conversion of water into wine at the wedding, walking on the waters, the calming of the storm and the nets filled.
In this very place, Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
But the greatest number of holy places are in Jerusalem.
The believers travel here on the Viacrucis or the Way of the Cross of Jesus (in Latin "See Pain").
It begins in the fortress of Antonio, the Pretoria, where the trial took place, and continues along the streets of the Old City, goes to the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha, the place of crucifixion, the Stone of the Unction and the burial place of Jesus.
In this same place is also the symbolic Christian Obbligation of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
And the monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem, built in the place where, according to a Christian legend, there was a tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus.
In Jerusalem is also the most sacred place for the Jews, the Wall of Lamentations; the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 C.E.
As tradition is, people of different religions leave here notes with their wishes, which will then become reality.
Perform a vertical journey
The ruins of the Masada Fortress were what was left of a secret refuge against the enemies, which Herod the Great commanded to build in 25 B.C.E. for his family.
They are found in mountain cliffs at a height of 450 m above sea level.
And get there by their own means, only those who dedicate themselves to climbing.
The others can reach this historic summit in the funicular.
And in the north of the country at an altitude of 1600-2040 m is the famous Hermón ski resort, where in the winter months there is a great influx of tourists.
Until there, bus services are offered from the foot of the hill.
The total length of the ski slopes is 45 km.
According to an ancient legend, on the top of the mountain supposedly inhabited pagan gods.
Visit unique museums
There are about 300 museums in this country.
On one trip you won't be able to visit them all.
But it is worth visiting at least five of them, the most interesting.
Among them is the Museum of Israel, located near the Knesset (Israel Parliament).
In it are preserved the ancient Dead Sea Manuscripts or Qumran Rolls, discovered in the caves of the Judean desert, and about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological pieces.
It is worth visiting the Art Museum in Tel Aviv.
In its exhibition of paintings there are canvases of impressionists and expressionists such as Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall or Picasso.
In Acre you can visit the Al Basha Bathroom, which are some rooms of ancient Turkish baths with model figures of visitors and bathers of that time.
In Caesarea it is worth passing through the exclusive private museum Ralli, where you can admire the sculptures of Rodin and Dalí.
There are no tourist guides or souvenir shops there.
The entrance is free, and donations are categorically not accepted.
The fifth, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, shows one of the most dramatic pages in history.
The most tragic section is the Children's Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children killed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter it and you find yourself in absolute darkness.
The stars shine.
And they ring the names of Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they lost their lives.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health
The three main tourist areas of Israel are on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of them there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphins and oceanographic museums.
It is curious that in the Red Sea they are bathed even in the winter months, as the temperature of the water does not lower than 21 degrees and the air is warmed up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and there they bathe throughout the year.
By the way, this sea, the most extraordinary in the world, is located at the lowest point on the planet: 417 m below sea level.
The blue waters there are a brine that can easily hold up to those who can’t swim.
The surrounding landscapes are truly beautiful.
People come here to pass treatment courses with salt water, salmur and curative bars and to fortify their health in cases of dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to order their broken nerves.
Touching the mysteries of antiquity
It retains the ancient part of Tel Aviv, the town of Jaffa, on the Mediterranean coast.
Through it was the famous maritime route that united Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, this is where Noah built his ark and Perseus rescued the beautiful Andromeda with whom, in this very place, he took a long and happy life.
Tourists love to walk through the narrow streets that bear the names of the signs of the Zodiac.
They say if you touch the walls on the street of your "mix" symbol, fortune will be favorable to you.
In Jaffa you can find newly married couples from all over Israel, and even from other countries to photograph.
And in Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can walk through the Roman theater, "take" the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of the Roman prosecutors, including Pontius Pilate.
The theatre, carefully restored, is now used for night concerts and opera shows.
