Traveling in any kind of public transport costs 6 sheqels and for this price you can travel doing transhipment for 1.5 hours.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, on Saturdays the Sabbath is celebrated.
From Friday night to Saturday sunset, markets and shops close and public transport interrupts their work.
But Sunday morning begins a new work week.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes in which milk and meat are combined.
There is a wide selection of beef and lamb-based dishes, soups and desserts prepared with coconut milk, the traditional Hebrew cream called hummus, a wide variety of sauces, falafel, which are balls of soft garbanzo, fruits and vegetables.
