It must be said that even those countries that we take as a model must face a large number of problems.
If it weren't, it wouldn't mean any benefit to them working with our office, would it?
With regard to the legislation of our country, what did the amendment to the law on public procurement mean to your Office? Is it in any way manifesting its impact?
Given that the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been manifested in the control proceedings.
Since we carry out ex post checks, there must be a certain delay.
For now, it is observed in the process of preparing future controls: we have started a new tool of "non-economic risk detection", by which we have passed nearly 14,000 public tenders, which have been analysed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, as the limits are modified, the conditions of some types of the selection process and similar.
Do you consider that the adoption of this law is beneficial or, rather, is an obstacle to the bureaucratic system?
I believe that this law is surely a step in the right direction and I hope so.
The problem that may arise is that the regulation "strengthened" and that it is impossible to comply with it.
Already with the previous regulations, the persons under control were linked to the contractor (e.g. in the case of regional operational programmes of the regional council), and each non-compliance with public procurement law meant breach of budgetary discipline.
So does it make sense to tighten the law like this?
I don't think that way.
The system must exclude those who want to attack it or take advantage of it and not punish those who make a formal decision, which has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only create greater bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We'll see where this road leads us.
The Prime Minister has recently stated that the ODS would not disturb entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called švarc system, with reference to the fact that it is autonomous only on paper. What does this mean?
Is the švarc system banned or allowed?
The law must be regulated in some way and, if it prohibits anything, then not even the prime minister of the government can prevent the Office's performance that has an obligation to carry out such checks and require obligations.
You can say, "We change the law and allow it," but you can't say that we will do as if nothing.
In the law on public procurement, legislation is quite strict as to how to act formally, and that is how it should be to protect public competition.
On the other hand, it is tragic that the candidate is excluded with the best offer for not meeting the formal requirements.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct.
