Poland and the cosmos.
At the meeting of ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency last week Poland was accepted as the twelfth member of the ESA. It is the second member country of the ESA of the former Eastern Europe bloc, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on 12 November 2008.
Poland began an intense collaboration with ESA in 1994 and during later years participated in the agency's project commission.
However, the path of Poland towards the cosmos began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already engaged in space flights prior to World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I recall, for example, the conference by A. Šternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, in which, on 6 December 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneering study "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the participants indifferent and, years later, Šternfeld recalled that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld won in France the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch prize for his "Introduction to cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned earlier, later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a series of books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, was known throughout the world and his contribution to science was rewarded when his name was placed on one of the craters of the hidden face of the moon.
Already in 1925 a strip was built in Poland, which was to be provided with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal is not known, nor are the project outbreaks known.
It is not clear whether the rocket was to be used for the start of the drain or for its braking.
Information on this web is limited to the collection in the press of the time.
From 1933 onwards, the Polish artillery began to dedicate itself to missiles.
The research was funded by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and Prof. Gustavem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the stored material, it is evident that the investigation reached the stage of the practical evidence.
However, with the arrival of the German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937 the prototype of a photo-electric hunting missile designed by engineer Rohoziński appeared in the specialized press and the following year was published the study "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza", by author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki.
Both projects were intended for military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the Interim Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Commitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was responsible for all draft missile techniques for military use and coordinated all the work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the start of the war.
Other studies dedicated to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The November 1954 issue of Problemmy magazine refers for the first time to society with four very extensive articles dedicated to astronomy.
In one of them, Prof. M. Subotowicze proposed the creation of a society that would be dedicated to cosmonautics.
At that time artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was obvious that cosmic research was a discipline with prospects for the future.
Since the beginning of 1956 the Polish Astronautics Society (PTA) had aspired to become a member of the International Astronautics Federation (founded in 1951) and in the fall of that year the PTA became a full member.
The following year the first PTA president, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became the vice president of the International Astronautics Federation.
He ran this post until his death in 1959.
From 1956 onwards, the PTA participated significantly in the development of the RM (Rakieta Meteorologicalzna) rocket, which was a success and became the first Polish rocket in which scientific research was carried out.
The first RM-1 type was completed in 1957 and was first launched on 10 October 1958.
The rocket had a peak of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm long and did not reach 5 kg weight.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed and in the summer of 1959 air tests of the two-stage RM-2 rockets were initiated in the Błędów desert.
The rocket measured 1.4 meters and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of developing rocket was to be the subject of real scientific study. The RM-34 rocket was to have an peak of 14.5 km and its mission would be to control the high wind.
However, work was suspended in 1962.
The successor of the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which were differentiated by the space available for scientific devices.
In the Meteor-1A rocket the space available for the volume was 0.4 liters, in the Meteor-1B 0.34 liters and in the Meteor-1C 0.62 liters.
The maximum peak in the three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968 the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Instituto Aeroeo, whose first air tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a useful weight of 10 kg up to 60 km in height.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 version was subsequently built.
It is also necessary to mention Poland's entry into the CoSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the CoSPAR National Committee two years later.
Under the Interkosmos programme, Poland joined the research of cosmic space on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonauta after Vladimir Remek.
