But the release of hostages in Iran, where the revolution had led to the constitution of the theocratic regime, was not within its reach.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which later intensified further with the failed attempt to free hostages by force.
The imprisoned diplomats were released 444 days after the negotiating intervention of the Algerian government.
In the U.S., their fate caused a wave of solidarity and animadversion against Iran.
The failure in Iran contributed decisively to Jimmy Carter's defeat of Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film "Argo" by director and actor Ben Affleck themes an episode of this story, which reaped a small success for America.
Shortly before taking over the embassy, six employees escaped from the building.
After a complicated journey, they ended up in the residence of the Canadian Embassy.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, helping them with an extravagant story: they came out with Canadian passports, as members of the film team that examined the location in the country for the production of a science fiction superproduction.
Gender combination
The plan presented by the expert on "exfiltration" Toni Mendez required Hollywood's collaboration.
To make the lie seem true, it was written about the film project in specialized journals, press conferences were organized, fictional production society even had a real office.
The details of the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film has been made from Tony Mendez's memories.
Affleck's film is a unique combination of various genres.
On the one hand, a realistic political thriller; on the other, a so-called "caper movie", the story of an episode that turned out well, a deception (an example can be the Ocean's Eleven series).
In the film are combined moods. On the one hand we find well documented sequences of Tehran. In the sequence of credits there are emblematic photographs of the time of events, which were shaped in the same way in the film; there are not many differences in this regard.
On the other hand, Hollywood's typical scenes are somewhat lighter, marked by irony and a slight exaggeration.
Also, scenes from the CIA Central and other institutions: worn men who analyze the situation at the negotiating table, in the corridors of the office, by telephone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in an excellent way.
The actor, who had been mocked, has become a respectable director and his way of acting has ceased to be the target of ironic comments.
Argo is his third feature film, after "Friendly, Adios" (2007) and the thriller "The Town. City of Thieves" (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck's first film in which action does not take place in the city of Boston, where it grew up.
Also, the sensitivity to capture the atmosphere of the place was a characteristic that placed directors of old movies above Hollywood standards.
And Affleck shows it in Argo, where Tehran is "ruined" in Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, in the reconstruction of verdic events. The introductory sequence of taking the embassy is impressive because of its synoptic capacity which, at the same time, transmits the emotion of the confusion and the lack of foresight that arises when, somewhere, history takes a step forward.
Affleck and his collaborators achieve a similar effect on fictional scenes (the imposter team at the Tehran bazaar).
Too many actions in too many places
The director had to accept the fact that an explained story does not offer much in the cinematographic sense of the most intriguing scenes.
And they are pretty well arranged. Sometimes something adds to the reality: here doesn't come all in such an elegant way (the scene in which the crisis is covered at Tehran airport, the deviation of a call to America and the unbridled search after its track become crazy).
The weakness of Argo is the lack of control that arises from the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman have a very funny role as Hollywood collaborators, although their characters deserved more space and are not, much less, the only ones in this film.
For these reasons, Affleck's film loses a bit of a dramatic trait, but it is a film that can be followed with a moderate interest, evaluate its realization and the retro style of a thriller that evokes in the 1970s.
But if it breaks down, that'll be hard.
As an evocation of a real story and as proof of how exaggerated the notions of omnipresentity and omniscience of secret services may be, is sufficient.
