We all have Internet, tablets and e-books.
Nobody likes to go into those old-fashioned libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a bedroom city located at the gates of Rotterdam that hardly deserves a fleeting visit, has the dubious honor of having stood with a record to forget.
The population of 80,000 has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counter this shameful situation, some years ago it was decided to contribute somehow to the general culture and copy the seven fictitious bridges that appear on euro banknotes in the form of decorated reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And so it was how political leaders decided that there was only one possibility to improve statistics: a library had to be built!
Winy Maas, from the Dutch architecture studio MVRDV, a whole master in the art of bar diagrams and responsible for fun buildings at pairing with cynics, took the theme with his usual serenity and appeared at the competition's presentation in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And as the jury looked at perplexing around him and shrugged his shoulders, Maas proceeded to stack the books by size forming a pyramid and concluded his brief speech with the following words: "Dear fellows:
Here you have it, my proposal for the Spijkenisse Book Mountain, the so-called `Boekenberg'."
Nine years later, the mountain of 30 million euros rises at the expected location.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is completed with underground parking, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of residential and town buildings.
In early November, the book mountains were awarded with the second "Best Library of NL 2012" prize.
In addition, the project is also nominated for the "Dutch National Wood Award 2012".
In this way, the small town lacking history, which so far had nothing but to offer a postmodern pedestrian zone and an incredibly ugly town hall behind whose white façade one would rather intuit a dairy center, now has a work of contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Path to the Book
The first impression is that it is a paradise of books under a cheese pan.
It is true that there is an elevator that carries us right to the center of this mountain mass, but the true lovers of space and reading do not use it, but rather merge with their topography at every step of their climb to the top.
The fully glazed interior is bright and easy to cover with the view, the brick floor collected and the elegant headlights unequivocally support the public condition of the library.
The urban environment is perfect.
Upon raising the view you can see the park banks, dogs and boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
"Usually the book shelves are arranged along the facade and in the center opens a huge dark room that is usually uncomfortable and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
What we've done is we put up the classic spatial configuration and take the reading area from the inside out.
The interior of the mountain is very well exploited: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education center and the maintenance room.
Special mention deserves the black shelves that assume the functions of wall covering, parapet and barandilla at the same time.
The sight, touch and smell are strange.
Even architects and civil engineers more a day shake their heads when they hear about this unknown material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," explains Joop Trouborst, project leader in the city of Spijkenisse.
And this is how one day, on a Frisian farm, we met with the right by-product from agriculture.
For many years, in the greenhouses and in the fields of the Netherlands, a plastic fabric of few millimetres of thickness has been used as a basis for holding the roots of crops.
It is a cheap and efficient material.
This fine fabric lasts two seasons and then is discarded.
For the library this fabric was first caught in such quantities until it obtained plates of four centimeters thick.
With heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material that smells of a new car mix and sports shoe.
After 105 steps you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous route of nearly 500 meters around the mountain awaits us the reward: from the café there is not only a fantastic view of the city, but also you can enjoy tasty Dutch croquettes and their ficus planted in huge pots.
These create a pleasant environment at the same time that maintains the air humidity suitable for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a New Soul
"Although it is difficult to believe it given its large crystallized surfaces, this building is an exemplary project in terms of ecology," Trouborst says.
The required heating and cooling are obtained from geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is located under a huge crystal pyramid, even in the most sunny days the sun shines only for a few hours inside.
The huge wooden circles located cross-sectionally on the glass façade serve to shade and absorb most of the sun's rays.
This creates a comfortable indoor climate.
The rest is about automatic blinds.
