Germany has abstained from the vote on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, expert in U.S.-Europe relations, this places Berlin in a rather dangerous diplomatic position.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany suggested that it would vote against the proposal to grant the Palestinian territories observer status of the United Nations.
However, Berlin finally abstained.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, because of the special relationship between the country and Israel, Germany should be careful.
But at the same time, I do not believe that it supports the American stance either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being overly critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to establishing a flight ban zone.
This has finally been declared by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to adopt a clear stance when important international issues are at stake?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because he is currently reorienting his foreign policy, moving away from a policy led by the United States, so to speak, and focusing on a German foreign policy.
And what makes things even more difficult is that Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
Therefore, the Germans are at a crossroads.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but are not accustomed to doing so.
I think they're still testing what their role will be, but they've already started the road to a "normal" foreign policy.
A similar foreign policy to countries such as France and Britain.
What exactly does a "normal" foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
It is a policy that, when it comes to national interests, stands ready to defend positions different from those of the United States or its European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy has a strong motivation for economic policy, i.e. exports and relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Near East.
German economic interests are to some extent different from those of other great powers and for that reason Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the stance taken with regard to the conflict in the Middle East and the UN vote?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf.
That is why it must be careful and not alienate from Arab public opinion or Arab elites.
This is important, of course.
But I would not give it so much importance since it is not a totally unilateral relationship.
However, they do play a key role in German considerations.
Has Germany undermined its relationship with the United States by refraining from voting in important decisions such as the Palestinian vote?
I believe that in Europe, and even in the United States, German stance has a huge degree of understanding.
For this reason, I do not think that there has been such a drastic rupture as in the case of Libya.
Perhaps Germany has managed to achieve a certain degree of respect.
After all, all this has done is to show that it is a country that takes seriously as an international actor and whose interests must be taken into account.
There are different views in Europe about the Palestinian initiative.
On the other hand, the U.S. has clearly shown itself in favour of a veto.
Is there a disparity of views between the US and many European nations?
These disparities have always existed because of U.S. internal policy.
I think the Obama government is secretly showing a great understanding of the European position.
But because of the political situation here, it is clear that the government cannot publicly defend that position.
I believe that the true disparity of views does not really have the extent to which it is attributed.
If we analyze the relations between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, we see that Obama is not enthusiastic about the policy he develops.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile the close relations it has with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of its main partners in the EU, on the other?
I think that is precisely what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
Of course it would be a little easier for Germans if there was a coherent and homogeneous European policy, but that is not the case.
