Bradley Manning did not report ill-treatment, as prosecutors say
Prosecutors try to deal with Bradley Manning's allegations of abuse during his stay in prison
The trial focuses on the Manning period in Quantico military prison in Virginia
The defense wants the case to be dismissed on the basis that Manning's imprisonment was severe
The army soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
The prosecutors tried to demonstrate on Friday that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the greatest leak of confidential information in the history of the United States, lost multiple opportunities to report the ill-treatment he now claims he suffered while he was under military arrest.
During the interrogation conducted by the prosecution at Manning in a pretrial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Prosecutor Ashden Fein stated that records of weekly visits by officers of the unit that Manning received during nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, do not show any complaints about the treatment he received.
The interrogation, which took place during a hearing held following the defence's request to dismiss the case since its imprisonment had been harsh and that this had already assumed sufficient punishment, arrived one day after Manning had testified that he had planned to commit suicide while he was in custody.
The army intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents while on duty in Iraq.
Later, WikiLeaks published the material on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of information.
In view of Friday, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms that the officers filled out after visits to Manning during their arrest at the military prison in Quantico, where he was imprisoned in maximum prison from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers would have asked Manning questions and noted their answers.
When Friday Fein asked about the forms, Manning recognized that he had qualified the treatment given to him by the captors as "excellent" and the treatment received at the facilities in general as "very professional".
The forms do not show any complaints of ill-treatment, although the officers asked Manning directly about the treatment he received, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concern about certain issues and that the officers visiting him had talked about those problems and had indicated that they would be addressed, but that they had not left a record of those issues in the register.
"They wrote 'no incidences' (after talking about the problems) but this doesn't necessarily mean that I didn't mention any problems," Manning said.
The judge, Colonel of the Denise Lind Army, also asked Manning why he had not denounced the treatment he received during the meeting that took place in January 2011 with a council to examine the suicide intentions he had expressed in a form months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during that meeting was to obtain the reduction of the "injury prevention" regime under which he was found.
The military said they had placed him under this restrictive regime, which is below the level of surveillance for possible suicide, to ensure their protection and safety for others.
"I wanted the older state to know that I was okay and (I wanted to) stop being under injury prevention... so I could enjoy what, from my point of view, is a better quality of life," Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for almost two months before being transferred to the military prison at sea base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and once lost knowledge because of heat.
He said that the fact that he was not allowed to know what was happening to him or what was happening in the outside world was very distressing.
"My world was reduced only to Camp Arafjon, to that cage," Manning explained on Thursday.
"I thought I was going to die in that cage."
Manning stated that, once transferred to Quantico, he spent most days in a small cell, at least for 21 hours and often for 23 hours, without company.
Manning said he was only allowed to have a mattress, a blanket, a chandelier, some clothes and glasses.
He explained that he was trying to move all the time, since it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
Manning claimed that he always had a light coming out pointing to his eyes while he was asleep.
He said that if the captors couldn't see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up to turn around again.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal claim in January 2011 on the treatment he received Manning.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth Military Prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge asked Manning about a claim he had made in his statement on Thursday, according to which, after having been forced one night to sleep naked in his cell of Quantico, he was forced during a morning counting to stand naked in front of the lockers and other prisoners.
Manning had testified that he had never been given the opportunity to cover himself with the blanket during the count.
During the judge's interrogation on Friday, Manning said he deduced by the order given to him by the locker that he should drop the blanket with which he could have been covered, but acknowledged that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified on Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of an attempt to prove to an officer that he did not pose a danger to himself.
Manning stated that he had told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his underwear or his chandeliers to self-injure himself but that he had not.
Manning testified that that night they had removed from his cell his underwear, his chandeliers and his glasses.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account the experiences he spent during his stay in prison and drastically reduce his sentence if he is convicted in the war council, which is expected to start early next year.
The defence stated that it plans to have Manning found guilty of minor crimes and to defend other accusations considered too extreme.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that the conditions of detention are justified.
The Pentagon has claimed that Manning was retained in accordance with the rules of application for any detainee who is in maximum custody in Quantico.
Charges against Manning include cooperation with the enemy, unlawfully provoking the publication of information on the Internet, filtering of national defence information and theft of property or public records.
If he is found guilty of all charges, he could face life imprisonment.
My Mexican-American identity crisis
Affirms that many were forced to leave Mexico due to lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to criticize those who have gone; says they remind Mexicans of those difficult times
Navarrette comments that Mexican-Americans are trapped between two worlds.
