But this was Mexico.
And, in my grandfather's homeland, tachographing or scripts were not necessary.
He was just American.
I speak Spanish, well enough to handle me during an interview in this language.
But I don't have a native's vocabulary level and I can't get rid of my American accent.
So I took my American passport and put myself in the queue of foreigners.
I thought about that moment this week when the elected president of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
On the agenda of the day, as long as the leaders of these two countries meet, there was immigration, drugs and trade.
Peña Nieto was also wishing to talk about the growth of the Mexican economy, one of the reasons why at the moment a Mexican is so likely to stay in Mexico like he ventures to go to the United States.
He wants to associate with the United States and Canada and create in North America a trade bloc in the style of the European Union.
In addition, Peña Nieto promised to continue to fight drug cartels in Mexico, although he did not give details.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never remember that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to yield half of its territory to gunpoint.
But for Mexicans, who think of centuries, not minutes, the elements they remember are everywhere.
So, at a time when a U.S. official says anything that brings the slightest criticism to Mexico, you start to hear complaints, both in the press and among the Mexican elite, about how Americans are usurping the sovereignty of their neighbours.
And the children of Moctezuma are on the rise to war.
And yet, for Mexico, the relationship that really poses a challenge is that of more than 35 million Mexican-Americans living in the United States.
Are we talking about resentment?
There's a lot.
In Mexico there are winners and losers, people for whom the country provides opportunities and others for which it is not.
The only reason there are so many people of Mexican descent living in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is that, at some point in our family tree, there was a person, perhaps the father or mother or any of the grandparents, to whom the door of opportunity was shut in Mexico and had to march north.
And most of the time that person fits into a certain profile: dark skin, a low level of studies, coming from a poor people, etc.
We are his descendants and are loyal to them.
Not Mexico.
And even though we may now be living the American dream, having gone to good schools and had good jobs, we can never lose sight that what we are living is that, the American dream, not the Mexican.
Sometimes our identity may not be clear, but our loyalty is.
It's for the United States.
Moreover, we are aware that many Mexicans belonging to the elite of the ruling class do not like us.
The feeling is mutual.
They see us as a reminder of a humiliating defeat and look at us above the shoulder as if we were from a lower category that is not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough and our ties with Mexico will never be strong enough.
In his view, our existence is synonymous with failure.
If our families hadn't failed in Mexico, they wouldn't have gone.
And now we wouldn't be trapped behind this silk curtain, living well in the United States but still as lonely souls.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally came to the United States when she was a girl, reminds me that there is this rock between Mexicans and Mexican-Americans because the first ones know more strongly who they are and the second thing bothers them.
Although she is a citizen of the United States, she is considered part of the two countries.
Meanwhile, many Mexican-Americans I know feel that they are not part of either.
We love to hear about the Mexican group Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
You have the best in every country, but you're not rooted in any of them.
In Mexico you see us as Americans.
And in the United States we are considered Mexicans.
Now, to make things even more complicated, so I've found out during my trip, some Mexican leaders and some intellectuals want to reconnect with the diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to work as improvised "ambassadors" of Mexico, representing their interests in the United States.
We would tell our American colleagues how fantastic it is to visit that country and push political leaders to strengthen their ties with Mexico.
Yes, of course...
That's not gonna happen.
There's too much resentment.
And, with unequal wages, galloping corruption and drug violence, many of us are not so sure it's a fantastic country.
I'm afraid you're gonna keep them alone with this idea, guys.
Fair enough.
If some Mexicans are not yet prepared to forgive the United States for the way they treated Mexico a century and a half ago, then they have to accept the fact that some Mexican-Americans are still upset about how their families were treated much less.
Hmmm.
Maybe we're more Mexicans than I thought.
