However, it admits that the new rules provide clearer guidance for developers, to whom they were previously hampered if they wanted to offer too many small units in a project.
Too stressed
Singapore is a state city.
While these new rules may be a step towards increasing the national birth rate, speaking with Singaporeans working in the financial district of the center seems to have little effect.
"People are very stressed, houses are expensive and so is education, so many people are postponing it," says a young executive.
Other people may have children.
"But it's important for me to have my own money and time," says another young man about 20 years old.
Men and women mention their career, stress and cost of property and education as reasons that prevent them from having children.
So, as much as the government is trying to push its citizens to have children, when it comes to babymaking, Singaporeans are the ones who have the last word.
